<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910312-0026</DOCNO><DOCID>910312-0026.</DOCID><HL>   Technology:   IBM to Offer Japan Firms   Details on Computer System</HL><DATE>03/12/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B4</SO><CO>   IBM JAPAN</CO><IN>COMPUTERS AND INFORMATION TECHNOLOGY (CPR)</IN><LP>   TOKYO -- International Business Machines Corp., in a bidto make its personal-computer operating system one of themajor standards here, said it will offer to share key aspectsof the system with Japanese companies.   Nobuo Mii, IBM-Japan's vice president in charge ofmanufacturing and development, said that some industryofficials estimate the move could boost the IBM-compatibleshare of the Japanese PC market to as much as 50% within twoyears, up from about 25% currently, and that it has inspiredup to 100 U.S. software companies to start writingIBM-compatible programs for the Japanese market.</LP><TEXT>   But some analysts cautioned that several attempts havebeen made in the past to try to encourage the spread ofIBM-compatible machines in Japan with only limited success.The Japan market so far has been dominated by NEC Corp.,which -- unlike IBM -- has always discouraged other makersfrom making machines compatible with its own exclusivearchitecture.   A major part of the new IBM offer is to share its advancedgraphics system, known as Video Graphics Array. Mr. Mii saidVGA is important for computer screens displaying Japanese&quot;kanji&quot; characters.   IBM also plans to offer access to its DOS J4.0/V system,and is considering giving Japanese companies access to itsOS/2 and Micro Channel Architecture systems, Mr. Mii said.</TEXT></DOC>